04295nam a22005415i 9780822376866DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223768667 a10.1515/97808223768662doi  a(DE-B1597)554302  a(OCoLC)884017025  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF2121 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a972.9a972.9/04a972.9041 aJames, C. L. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Life of Captain Cipriani :bAn Account of British Government in the West Indies, with the pamphlet The Case for West-Indian Self Government /cC. L. R. James. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe C. L. R. James Archives00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tThe Life of Captain Cipriani: An Account of British Government in the West Indies -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tCHAPTER I. The People Concerned -- tCHAPTER II. Early Days -- tCHAPTER III. With the B.W.I.R. -- tCHAPTER IV. Captain Cipriani and the Labour Movement -- tCHAPTER V. Captain Cipriani and the Legislative Council -- tCHAPTER VI. Th e Municipality and the Trinidad Electricity Company -- tCHAPTER VII. The Divorce Legislation -- tCHAPTER VIII. Personal -- tTHE CASE FOR WEST-INDIAN SELF GOVERNMENT -- tCONTENTS -- tCHAPTER I. The English in the West Indies -- tCHAPTER II. The Governor in-Executive-Council -- tCHAPTER III. The Legislative Council0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Life of Captain Cipriani (1932) is the earliest full-length work of nonfiction by the Trinidadian writer C. L. R. James, one of the most significant historians and Marxist theorists of the twentieth century. It is partly based on James's interviews with Arthur Andrew Cipriani (1875-1945). As a captain with the British West Indies Regiment during the First World War, Cipriani was greatly impressed by the service of black West Indian troops and appalled at their treatment during and after the war. After his return to the West Indies, he became a Trinidadian political leader and advocate for West Indian self-government. James's book is as much polemic as biography. Written in Trinidad and published in England, it is an early and powerful statement of West Indian nationalism. An excerpt, The Case for West-Indian Self Government, was issued by Leonard and Virginia Woolf's Hogarth Press in 1933. This volume includes the biography, the pamphlet, and a new introduction in which Bridget Brereton considers both texts and the young C. L. R. James in relation to Trinidadian and West Indian intellectual and social history. She discusses how James came to write his biography of Cipriani, how the book was received in the West Indies and Trinidad, and how, throughout his career, James would use biography to explore the dynamics of politics and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aBrereton, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376866zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376866.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles